 to similar future cases. Originalists are correct about this much. But good faith does not forbid the Justices to refine and adjust their interpretive theories in response to the novel challenges that new cases present. Fallon argues that theories of constitutional interpretation should be works in progress, not rigid formulas laid down in advance of the unforeseeable challenges that life and experience generate. Law and Legitimacy in the Supreme Court offers theories of constitutional law and judicial legitimacy that accept many tenets of legal realism but reject its corrosive cynicism. Fallon’s account both illuminates current practice and prescribes urgently needed responses to a legitimacy crisis in which the Supreme Court is increasingly enmeshed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aJudicial processzUnited States. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzUnited States. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067498611440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674986114423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674986114.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles